The band gap value of CQDs can be calculated using the Tauc Plot equation [40]. The following is the Tauc Plot equation;
(1) (αhν)n = A(hν−Eg)
Where α is the absorption coefficient, hν is the photon energy, A is the characteristic constant of the material, and n is equal to 1/2 for indirect transitions and 2 for direct transitions. E.g. can be found by extrapolating the linear part of the (αhν)2 graph to the x-axis (α = 0) [41]. The calculated band gap value for CQDs is around 3.2 eV. As shown in Fig. 1b, the resulting band gap energy is similar to research conducted by Ref. [40], where the band gap energy of CQDs is around 3.51 eV–2.52 eV, which indicates that the synthesised CQDs are semiconducting.

EIS measurements were conducted on a three-electrode system with a frequency range from 100 kHz to 10 MHz and a signal amplitude of 5 mV (see Table 3
                           ). The EIS analysis results show that the curve consists of two distinct parts: a semicircular region at high frequencies and a straight-line region at low frequencies (Fig. 7
                           ). Typically, the semicircle pattern on the Nyquist plot appears at high frequencies and reflects a rapid electrochemical response influenced by the charge transfer process in the supercapacitor electrode [61]. However, in this case, the semicircle pattern tends to become more linear with slight curvature at high frequencies, possibly due to the dominance of the intrinsic resistance of the electrode material and the overall electrochemical system at those frequencies.
